Divination methods are present in the human history since the beggining. 


Usualy of them have a simple binary yes/no form, as a coin flipping and are used to consult God or gods about the correct action on a certain situation.

In the Hebrew Bible there are several instances where the Urim and Thummim were used or mentioned. Here are some notable examples:

In Numbers 27:18-21, the Urim and Thummim are mentioned in the context of seeking guidance from God. When Joshua is appointed as the new leader of the Israelites after Moses, he is instructed to stand before the High Priest Eleazar, who would use the Urim to seek God's counsel on important decisions.

In 1 Samuel 28:6, King Saul seeks guidance from God through various means, including the Urim and Thummim, but receives no answer. This event takes place during a time when Saul has fallen out of favor with God, leading to his eventual demise.

In 1 Samuel 30:7-8, David asks the High Priest Abiathar to bring him the ephod, which contained the Urim and Thummim. David then uses the Urim and Thummim to seek God's guidance on whether he should pursue the Amalekites who had raided his camp and taken his people captive. God answers through the Urim and Thummim, advising David to pursue the Amalekites.

These instances demonstrate the importance of the Urim and Thummim in the Hebrew Bible as tools to seek divine guidance and to make critical decisions, especially during times of conflict or uncertainty.

